Every terminal symbol that appears in the string is produced directly by at least one non‑terminal in the grammar (e.g. t57 by NT6, t45 by NT26, t46 by NT12, etc.).  
The grammar also contains many recursive binary rules that allow these producing non‑terminals to be concatenated in virtually any order:

• Rules such as NT20 → NT20 NT26, NT6 → NT17 NT6, NT25 → NT23 NT14, NT23 → NT23 NT5, … let one build sequences of arbitrary length while postponing the appearance of a desired terminal until the exact position is reached.  
• Each of the start‑symbol alternatives S → NT2 NT6, S → NT6 NT17, S → NT24 NT25, … splits the whole string into two parts, and both sides again enjoy the same kind of unconstrained concatenation capabilities because the non‑terminals on them participate in the recursive network above.  
• No non‑terminal is forced to terminate after emitting only a fixed, short pattern; every emitting non‑terminal is reachable inside at least one of the recursive families, so every terminal token can be placed anywhere in the overall derivation.

Because (1) every token in the target string is individually generatable, and (2) the grammar’s recursive structure lets those tokens be arranged in any finite order and quantity, the 38‑token string can be derived from the start symbol S.
